<paragraph id="E97036DD3F7FFFE8FF76FEA4FD07FEDC" blockId="74.[151,1437,290,964]" box="[151,743,290,317]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
Size. Maximum size 
<quantity id="2E379B383F7FFFE8FE65FEA4FE5BFEDD" box="[388,443,290,316]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" unit="cm" value="4.0">4 cm</quantity>
total length (Miller 1986).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1D565563F7FFFE8FF26FEC0FDF1FC25" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" type="description">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F7FFFE8FF26FEC0FF00FDF4" blockId="74.[151,1437,290,964]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
Morphology. D VI (VI–VII) + I,9–11; A I,8–10; P 17–20 (Miller 1986). Small goby with subcylindrical body, laterally compressed towards caudal fin, head moderately small. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7FFFE8FC84FEEFFB1CFE65" bold="true" box="[869,1276,361,388]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Typically short and rounded snout</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7FFFE8FAE8FEECFE55FE46" bold="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Eyes lateral, interorbital space wide.</emphasis>
Caudal peduncle slender, clearly lower than body depth. Dorsal fins of similar height, the first dorsal fin with more or less rounded margin and no elongated spines. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7FFFE8FBC8FE37FEC6FE0E" bold="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Caudal fin truncate to slightly emarginate.</emphasis>
Scales present on body, usually visible on photographs at least dorsally. Predorsal area naked (Miller 1986).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F7FFFE8FF26FD98FDCAFD0C" blockId="74.[151,1437,290,964]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
Live coloration. Background color 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7FFFE8FD83FD9BFC65FDD9" bold="true" box="[610,901,541,568]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">beige to reddish orange</emphasis>
, with 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7FFFE8FC34FD9BFECDFDBD" bold="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">alternating narrow dark and whitish vertical bars</emphasis>
, more numerous in males. Irregular dark markings along back. Sometimes 4 pale dorsal saddles, first below origin of second dorsal fin, last on rear caudal peduncle; 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7FFFE8FCBAFDE0FEEFFD42" bold="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">a large red or blackish triangular spot on base of caudal fin</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F7FFFE8FEFEFD0CFE94FD44" box="[287,372,650,677]" captionStart="FIGURE 64" captionStartId="74.[151,250,1841,1865]" captionTargetBox="[171,1416,988,1818]" captionTargetId="figure-321@74.[171,1416,988,1818]" captionTargetPageId="74" captionText="FIGURE 64. Live coloration in aquariumof Pomatoschistus knerii. Photo by J. Vukić, Krk Island, Croatia, northern Adriatic Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601761" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601761/files/figure.png" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Fig. 64</figureCitation>
). May be 2 red or dark bars below eye, first reaching corner of mouth, second on cheek. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7FFFE8FA82FD0FFD77FD26" bold="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">First dorsal fin with three oblique orange stripes</emphasis>
, second sometimes with series of brown spots (Miller 1986; 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F7FFFE8FADEFD28FEFFFD0D" author="Kovacic, M. &amp; Pillon, R. &amp; Louisy, P." pageId="74" pageNumber="75" refId="ref59210" refString="Kovacic, M., Pillon, R. &amp; Louisy, P. (2017 b) Signalisation de / Record of Pomatoschistus knerii, 22 March 2017 (obs. 16 June 2016, photo  3609). Fish Watch Forum, Louisy, P. &amp; Francour, P. (Ed.). Available from: https: // www. fish-watch. org (accessed 28 September 2021)" type="url" year="2017">
Kovačić 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7FFFE8FF76FD55FF28FD0D" box="[151,200,722,748]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">et al</emphasis>
. 2017b
</bibRefCitation>
; present work, 
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F7FFFE8FE2BFD54FDFEFD0C" box="[458,542,722,749]" captionStart="FIGURE 64" captionStartId="74.[151,250,1841,1865]" captionTargetBox="[171,1416,988,1818]" captionTargetId="figure-321@74.[171,1416,988,1818]" captionTargetPageId="74" captionText="FIGURE 64. Live coloration in aquariumof Pomatoschistus knerii. Photo by J. Vukić, Krk Island, Croatia, northern Adriatic Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601761" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601761/files/figure.png" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Fig. 64</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F7FFFE8FF26FD70FD18FCF1" blockId="74.[151,1437,290,964]" box="[199,760,758,784]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
Similar species. 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F7FFFE8FE9EFD70FD90FCF1" authorityName="Miller" authorityYear="1982" box="[383,624,758,784]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Pomatoschistus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bathi">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7FFFE8FE9EFD70FD90FCF1" box="[383,624,758,784]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Pomatoschistus bathi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F7FFFE8FD9FFD71FD11FCF1" authorityName="Benthic" baseAuthorityName="Heckel" baseAuthorityYear="1837" box="[638,753,758,784]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Pomatoschistus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="quagga">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7FFFE8FD9FFD71FD6FFCF1" box="[638,655,759,784]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7FFFE8FD7CFD71FD11FCF1" box="[669,753,759,784]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">quagga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F7FFFE8FF26FC9CFCD8FC9D" blockId="74.[151,1437,290,964]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
Habitat. Infralittoral species, mostly encountered between 
<quantity id="2E379B383F7FFFE8FCAFFC9CFC42FCD5" box="[846,930,794,820]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="0.0" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" unit="m" value="5.0" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="0.0">0–10 m</quantity>
depth (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F7FFFE8FC12FC9CFB73FCD5" author="Kovacic, M." box="[1011,1171,794,820]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" pagination="1051 - 1055" refId="ref57812" refString="Kovacic, M. (2003) Hyperbenthic gobies in the Kvarner area, Adriatic Sea. Journal of Fish Biology, 63, 1051 - 1055. https: // doi. org / 10.1046 / j. 1095 - 8649.2003.00221. x" type="journal article" year="2003">Kovačić 2003</bibRefCitation>
), but known down to 
<quantity id="2E379B383F7FFFE8FA61FC9CFF4DFCB9" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" unit="m" value="45.0">45 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F7FFFE8FF5BFCB8FE45FCB8" author="Kovacic, M. &amp; Pillon, R. &amp; Louisy, P." box="[186,421,830,857]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" refId="ref59210" refString="Kovacic, M., Pillon, R. &amp; Louisy, P. (2017 b) Signalisation de / Record of Pomatoschistus knerii, 22 March 2017 (obs. 16 June 2016, photo  3609). Fish Watch Forum, Louisy, P. &amp; Francour, P. (Ed.). Available from: https: // www. fish-watch. org (accessed 28 September 2021)" type="url" year="2017">
Kovačić 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F7FFFE8FEFEFCB9FEAFFCB9" box="[287,335,830,856]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">et al</emphasis>
. 2017b
</bibRefCitation>
), often hovering 
<quantity id="2E379B383F7FFFE8FDBEFCB8FD2DFCB9" box="[607,717,830,857]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" unit="cm" value="30.0" valueMax="50.0" valueMin="10.0">10–50 cm</quantity>
above the substrata, on sand near rock and 
